1. Convert the given strings to integers in base b using the `Integer.parseInt()` method.
2. Iterate while the integer l is less than or equal to the integer r.
3. Calculate the remainder of dividing l by b and add it to the count.
4. Update l by dividing l by b and update r by dividing r by b.
5. Calculate the remainder of dividing r by b and add it to the count.
6. Update r by multiplying r by b.
7. Update l by dividing l by b and update r by multiplying r by b.
8. Return the count.

The time complexity is O(log(log(n)) because we perform log(n) iterations, where n is the length of the string r. Each iteration involves two divisions and two modulo operations, which have a time complexity of O(log(n)). The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space for the variables count and l, r. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs basic arithmetic operations and does not consume significant energy.

